isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.56) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.26. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.26, p < .001, 95% CI [13.02, 14.04]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.37, p = 0.715, 95% CI [-0.86, 0.59]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.14])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.05, S.E. = 0.40, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.84, -2.27]; Std. beta = -0.75, 95% CI [-0.95, -0.56])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -2.09, S.E. = 3.06, p = 0.496, 95% CI [-8.08, 3.91]; Std. beta = -0.51, 95% CI [-1.99, 0.96])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.48, S.E. = 0.59, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.62, -1.33]; Std. beta = -0.61, 95% CI [-0.89, -0.33])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -3.99, S.E. = 3.43, p = 0.245, 95% CI [-10.70, 2.73]; Std. beta = -0.98, 95% CI [-2.64, 0.67])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
